   Municipal Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Most actively traded municipal bonds closed 1 1/4 to 1 1/2
points lower, taking their cue from the Treasury market and
reacting to skyrocketing oil prices.
   The "only hope" for municipals is that some support will
come from the market's shortage of bonds and expectations for
higher taxes in a number of states, said one trader.
   Among the actively traded issues, the New Jersey Turnpike
Authority's 7.20% of 2018 ended 1 1/4 lower at 97 7/8,
causing the yield to shoot up to 7.36% from 7.26% late
Friday.
   In the new-issue sector, the market's bearish mood caused
a less-than-warm reception for an issue by Maricopa County,
Ariz., of $75 million of general-obligation bonds.
   The bonds, won by a Marine Midland Capital Markets Corp.
group, were priced for reoffering to yield from 6.65% in 1999
to 6.90% in 2003.
   There was an unsold balance of approximately $60 million
in late trading.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-, Asset-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage securities ended sharply lower, following the
path of Treasury issues.
   Among actively traded issues, Government National Mortgage
Association 9% issues were down 1 21/32 at 96 9/32, Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp. 9.5% issues were off 1 9/32 at 98
12/32, and Federal National Mortgage Association 9% issues
were down 1 17/32 at 96 11/32.
   In new-issue activity, a $150 million offering of Western
Financial auto-loan backed certificates was priced by
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   The certificates, backed by California loans on new and
used autos, carry an 8.35% coupon, and were priced at 99.896
to yield 8.51%.
